The Proposal: -

Moje Tatra in Amravati district, Ta. The original budget of the tap water supply scheme at Dharani was prepared by the Executive Engineer, Rural Water Supply Department, Zilla Parishad, Amravati vide Reference No. Technical approval is provided under Section 2. Also, Reference No. 1 under Rs. 69,39,477 - Administrative approval has been granted for such a modest price. Also, Reference No. 5 of the Department. The tender for the additional rate of the scheme has been operationally approved by the letter of the 28.01.2023र DG. The Chief Executive Officer, Zilla Parishad, Amravati has proposed to give revised administrative approval to the proposed tap water supply scheme vide Reference Letter No. 4 here. The letter dated 04.09.2024 has been submitted to the government. Reference No. 3 here. Under the letter dated 23.08.2024, the government was under consideration to grant revised administrative approval to the price as per the revised technical approval given by the Executive Engineer, Rural Water Supply Department, Zilla Parishad, Amravati.
The Government's Decisions:

Mojhe Tatra in Amravati district under the "Jal Jeevan Mission Programme," Ta. The tap water supply scheme in Dharani has been affected by the increase in the cost of the scheme due to flood and surcharge on Goods and Services Tax (GST) rates and technical changes, subject to the following conditions: Rs. 79,56,539 - (Rs.

Nineteen hundred and fifty-six thousand five hundred and forty-nine only) is being approved by the revised administration.
Conditions
1) The CEO / Chief Engineer will be responsible for completing all the remaining works within the prescribed time frame at the above mentioned revised cost.
2) The terms and conditions mentioned while granting the revised technical approval as well as the original administrative approval agreed upon for the scheme should be strictly adhered to.

3) On completion of the scheme, it should be handed over to the concerned Gram Panchayat. The concerned Gram Panchayat / Zilla Parishad shall be responsible for taking over the scheme within one month from the date of receipt of intimation from the concerned Executive Engineer, Rural Water Supply Department, Zila Parishad that the scheme has actually been completed. Immediately after the actual completion of the scheme, a joint inspection of the scheme should be conducted by the concerned Executive Engineer, Zilla Parishad and concerned Gram Panchayat officials and any defects found in such inspection should be corrected before handing over the scheme.

4) The Gram Panchayat / Zilla Parishad concerned shall not receive any assistance from the Government for meeting the recurring expenditure incurred annually for implementation, maintenance, repairs (including special modifications), reduction in the scheme or renovation of machinery.
5) On completion of the scheme, it will be mandatory for the local body (concerned Gram Panchayat / Zila Parishad) to implement the scheme. The accounts of the scheme should also be closed.

6) According to a CAG report in 2013, 21 per cent of the water supply schemes in the state appear to have been shut down due to poor maintenance / non-payment of electricity bills. In fact, in order to make the scheme financially viable, it will be the responsibility of the concerned Gram Panchayat / Zilla Parishad to increase the water tariff as per the requirement.
7) Action should be taken in accordance with the prevailing policy on extortion.
8) It shall be the responsibility of the Zilla Parishad that the present scheme shall not be revised under any circumstances.

9) Since administrative expenditure is not permissible under the Jal Jeevan Mission, it should be excluded if any administrative expenditure of 4% has been taken up in the revised budget of the scheme.
